  "invoice-vs-receipt-vs-quotation": {
    title: "Invoice vs Receipt vs Quotation: What's the Difference?",
    description:
      "Confused about invoice vs receipt vs quotation? Learn what each document means, when to use it, and how they fit together тАФ with free templates for all three.",
    date: "2026-02-20",
    updated: "2026-06-11",
    readMins: 4,
    keywords: ["invoice vs receipt", "quotation vs invoice", "difference between invoice and receipt", "receipt vs invoice"],
    excerpt:
      "Invoice, receipt, and quotation are easy to mix up. Here's what each one means, when to send it, and how they work together in the sales cycle.",
    body: [
      { type: "p", text: "A customer hands you cash, says thanks, and asks you to email тАЬan invoiceтАЭ for it. What they actually need is a receipt; the invoice moment passed the second the money changed hands. The mix-up is harmless in conversation and expensive in bookkeeping, because quotations, invoices, and receipts mark three different moments in a sale, and your records only stay clean when each appears at the right one." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Three documents, three moments" },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "<strong>Quotation:</strong> before the work. States what the job will cost so the client can say yes.",
        "<strong>Invoice:</strong> after the work, before the money. Requests payment by a set date.",
        "<strong>Receipt:</strong> after the money. Confirms payment was received and closes the loop.",
      ] },
      { type: "p", text: "Not every sale needs all three. A market stall takes cash and hands over a receipt; a six-week project usually generates the full set. The order, though, never changes." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Quotation: the price, agreed in advance" },
      { type: "p", text: "A quotation is your offer in writing: itemised prices, the total, a validity period, and any assumptions (тАЬassumes weekday accessтАЭ, тАЬexcludes partsтАЭ). It isn't a request for payment, yet it does the most important commercial work of the three, because it's what the client compares against the final bill. A quote that says тАЬGarden clearance and re-turfing: $1,850, valid 30 daysтАЭ prevents the dispute that a vague verbal estimate invites. The craft is covered in our <a href=\"/blog/how-to-write-a-quotation\">guide to writing quotations</a>." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Invoice: the request for payment" },
      { type: "p", text: "Once the work is delivered, the invoice converts the agreement into a debt with a deadline: a unique number, both parties' details, itemised lines, any tax, the total, and a due date. It's the document accountants and tax offices care most about, since it's the formal record that money is owed. Sticking with the garden job, the invoice might read: тАЬClearance and re-turfing, per quote QU-031: $1,850. Sleeper repair (agreed 14 May): $150. Total due: $2,000, payable by 28 May.тАЭ" },
      { type: "h2", text: "Receipt: proof the money arrived" },
      { type: "p", text: "The receipt is the shortest of the three and the only one issued after payment. It states what was paid, when, and how (тАЬ$2,000 received by bank transfer, 26 MayтАЭ). Buyers rely on receipts for expense claims, warranties, and tax records, which is why тАЬcan I get a receipt?тАЭ follows so many payments. Issue one promptly and unprompted for cash especially, since cash leaves no bank trail of its own." },
      { type: "h2", text: "How they chain together" },
      { type: "ol", items: [
        "You send a <strong>quotation</strong>; the client approves it in writing.",
        "You deliver the work and send an <strong>invoice</strong> that mirrors the quote, plus any agreed changes.",
        "The client pays; you issue a <strong>receipt</strong> and file all three together.",
      ] },
      { type: "p", text: "Filed as a set, the three documents tell the whole story of a job: what was promised, what was billed, what was paid. When a question surfaces months later, that bundle answers it without anyone relying on memory." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Where people trip up" },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "<strong>Sending an invoice after payment.</strong> If the money has arrived, the right document is a receipt (or an invoice clearly marked тАЬPAIDтАЭ, which does the same job).",
        "<strong>Treating a quote as a bill.</strong> A quotation can't be chased for payment. If the client accepted your quote and the work is done, invoice them.",
        "<strong>Issuing receipts before funds clear.</strong> A receipt says the money arrived. Wait for the transfer to land, not for the promise of it.",
        "<strong>Mismatched references.</strong> Quote, invoice, and receipt should cite each other so anyone can trace the chain.",
      ] },
      { type: "h2", text: "A fourth cousin: the proforma" },
      { type: "p", text: "Between quotation and invoice sits the <a href=\"/proforma-invoice\">proforma invoice</a>, a preview of the final bill used mostly in trade and exports. It looks like an invoice but isn't payable and never enters your accounts; think of it as a quotation wearing an invoice's clothes." },
      { type: "callout", text: "One tool covers the whole chain: <a href=\"/\">switch between quotation, invoice, and receipt in PDF Bill Builder</a> and download each as a free PDF." },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: "Is a quotation legally binding?", a: "A quotation is an offer, not a demand for payment. Once the client accepts it, it can form part of a binding agreement depending on your terms, which is why stating a validity period and your assumptions matters." },
      { q: "Can one tool create invoices, receipts, and quotations?", a: "Yes. PDF Bill Builder lets you switch between invoice, receipt, and quotation with one click, keeping the same details and layout, and download any of them as a PDF." },
      { q: "Can a quotation turn into an invoice?", a: "That's exactly how it should work. Once the client accepts the quote and the work is delivered, the invoice repeats the quoted lines plus any agreed changes, and adds a number, a due date, and payment details." },
      { q: "Which document should I send when a customer pays a deposit?", a: "A receipt for the deposit amount, referencing the quote or invoice it relates to. Your final invoice then shows the full price, the deposit already received, and the balance still due." },
    ],
  },

